@node "intro" "What the deuce is it this time?"
@toc "alko"

            Phoar. Here you have the @{b}pt/psid-module@{ub} player of the 90s.
            This baby uses external libraries to give you the
            possibility to keep in pace with the developement.
            When a new library is released, you'll just have
            install it and enjoy the fruits of the present day.

            PSID-module autodetection provided. Marvellous!
            Thanks to Ron Birk and Per Hĺkan Sundell for their
            playsid.library and Mattias Karlsson for his
            ptreplay.library.

            HPlayer gives you the possibility to pack your
            musics and even the showed pictures with any of
            the packers the unpack.library supports.
            You need to have the packer, which you used to
            pack the files, in its path. Glance through the packers
            the unpack.library @{"support" link "suppo" 0}s.

            HPlayer uses your system's CHIP-memory to its
            maximum. Every single kilobyte of it will be utilized
            when you run HPlayer.

            When your machine runs out of memory, it doesn't
            mean that you won't be able to watch those nice
            b&w pictures: Your visual voyage just becomes
            little duller. HPlayer loads data until it runs
            out of memory and starts playing.

            If an error occurs or system runs out of memory
            before reaching the play-part you'll be
            notified with a yellow lightning or a message box.
            100% assembler coded and 100% system compability
            ensured. No GURUs or look-a-likes.

            If you think there are too many pictures in the
            Data - drawer, just delete the ones you don't
            need, but leave atleast one picture... Much better
            idea is to pack the MultiMedia-format pictures
            into a smaller size. Script which does the job
            automatically is provided in the Scripts-directory.

            Also, remember to check out the splendid tunes from
            Examples-directory.

            @{b}We make no compromises@{ub}.
@endnode

@node "req" "Ruskea James ruskea"
@toc "alko"

            Requirements: An @{b}Amiga@{ub} computer supplied with
                          the @{b}AGA@{ub} chipset. This program is CHIP
                          memory hungry, and the more chip you have
                          available the more pictures you'll be able
                          to see.
@endnode

@node "usage" "Pump up the volume"
@toc "alko"

            @{b}Usage: HPlayer [filename] [enter]@{ub}

            For example: "HPlayer Examples/example.mod"

            The player has no option keys, but who needs them
            anyway? When an error occurs you'll be notified.

            If you'd like to copy the HPlayer to your C
            directory you'll need to Assign HPLAYER:
            to your HPlayer - directory. By assigning the
            player can locate the precious data files.

            > Assign HPLAYER: SYS:HPlayer [ENTER]

            Quitting takes place by pressing the escape key
            or left mouse button while the show is on.

            If you are playing a PlaySID-module, you can
            change the tune by pressing + or - keys
            in the numeric keypad on the right.
@endnode

@node "hist" "No scavengers nor squirrels here."
@toc "alko"

            v1.00 - First public release.
                    More releases will perhaps follow, they
                    strongly depend on the amount of email feedback.
                    @{b}We have the knowledge to provide you with
                    many new pictures.@{ub}
                    This version was tweaked and tested like hell.
@endnode

